            <h2>About:</h2>
            <p class="descriptions">
                Philodendrons add a unique, tropical appearance to the indoor environment and are often undemanding regarding their care as long as certain requirements are met. Available to indoor growers are a wide variety of species from which to choose, featuring distinguishing characteristics such as leaf shape, size, color, and growing habit. Large growing species such as <a href="?action=article&species=Philodendron Giganteum">philodendron giganteum</a> provide a bold, dramatic effect with their enormous foliage while smaller, colorful, <a href="?action=article&species=Philodendron Hybrids: Prince of Orange, Black Cardinal, Moonlight">hybridized species</a> work well under lower light conditions and are suitable for a window sill or desk.
            </p>
            <p class="descriptions">
                If you are new to philodendrons, please read the following section on basic plant structure and growth habit. Becoming familiar with these aspects of philodendrons will allow you to better understand individual species and improve your decisions when purchasing a specimen for your home. You might also want to check out the <a href="?action=growingGuide">growing guide</a>, which offers soil recommendations, watering advice, and more.
            </p>
            <p class="descriptions notice">
                <span class="boldText">Note:</span> Mature leaf sizes listed on this web site refer to approximated leaf blade sizes observed in nature and are a way to compare leaf sizes among different species. Indoor specimens do not grow nearly as large and can take several years to reach their adult form.
            </p>
