        <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-12">
            <div class="traits">
                <h2>Basic Plant Structure:</h2>
                <ul class="fact-list">
                    <li>
                        <span class="boldText">Cataphyll</span> &ndash; A leaf-like structure that protects a new leaf as it emerges.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="boldText">Petiole</span> &ndash; What most people refer to as a stem is actually described scientifically as a petiole. It is the support that connects the leaf blade to the actual stem of the plant.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="boldText">Stem</span> &ndash; The base, or stalk of the plant, which roots and petioles grow from.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="boldText">Aerial Root</span> &ndash; Produced above the soil from the side of the stem. The purpose of these roots is to climb around a support or grow down into the soil to absorb nutrients and help anchor the plant.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <figure class="d-block d-md-none my-4">
                <img src="<%= `${process.env.CDN_ENDPOINT}Giganteum4.jpg` %>" alt="Photograph of the structure of a philodendron" />
                <figcaption class="boldText">Basic structure of a philodendron.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            <div class="traits">
                <h2>Growth Habits:</h2>
                <p class="descriptions">
                    There are three basic growth habits which philodendrons exhibit and are important for the grower to consider when purchasing a plant.
                </p>
                <ul class="fact-list">
                    <li>
                        <span class="boldText">Climbing</span> &ndash; Grow tall vertically and use aerial roots to cling to a support. Some species produce a thick stem that resembles a tree trunk while others are simply vines that grow even higher. See <a href="?action=article&species=Philodendron Warszewiczii">philodendron warszewiczii</a> and <a href="?action=article&species=Philodendron Squamiferum">philodendron squamiferum</a> for examples.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="boldText">Self-heading</span> &ndash; Grow low to the ground and do not climb, instead producing new leaves from the center of the plant in a clumping manner. See <a href="?action=article&species=Philodendron Hybrids: Prince of Orange, Black Cardinal, Moonlight">philodendron hybrids</a> for an example.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="boldText">Creeping</span> &ndash; Do not climb and instead spread the stem along the ground while producing upright petioles. See <a href="?action=article&species=Philodendron Pastazanum">philodendron pastazanum</a> for an example.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>		
    </div>
</section>